      <hedline>
        <hl1>Vouchers' Silver Lining</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Aneesa Arshad says example of so-called ineffectiveness of vouchers cited in Richard Rothstein's July 3 Lessons column fails to note success of many private schools with voucher program in instilling discipline, morality and religious ethics into children</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Failed Schools? The Meaning Is Unclear'' (Lessons column, July 3):</p>
        <p>Richard Rothstein writes that a study that compared Cleveland students who received vouchers with public school students who wanted vouchers but did not receive them showed ''no significant differences in scores.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Failed Schools? The Meaning Is Unclear'' (Lessons column, July 3):</p>
        <p>Richard Rothstein writes that a study that compared Cleveland students who received vouchers with public school students who wanted vouchers but did not receive them showed ''no significant differences in scores.''</p>
        <p>But this example of the so-called ineffectiveness of vouchers fails to note the success of many private schools with the voucher program in instilling discipline, morality and religious ethics into our children. It is these factors, combined with a good education, that will help our children and our country succeed.</p>
        <p>ANEESA ARSHAD  Mequon, Wis., July 3, 2002</p>
      </block>
